Book 3
== The ring continues southeast while the company deals with matters in the southwest.
    The Departure of Boromir
    -- Boromir tells Aragorn of his betrayal, and they respect Boromir's legacy.
        Charcters
            Aragorn
            Boromir, heir of Denathor
            Gimli
            Orcs
        Places
            Parth Galen of Emyn Muil
            Barad-dur, stronghold of Sauron
        Syntactical Summary
            Aragorn hears the horn of Boromir sound, and finds Boromir dying in the woods when he arrives. Boromir tells of his betrayal, and is not able to say more before life leaves his body. Gimli and Legolas appear to find Aragorn over Boromir, and the three place his body in a boat and leave his fate to the river Anduin. After singing songs in Boromir's memory, the trio pieces together the puzzle of the hobbits, and they resolve to find Merry and Pippin and leave Frodo and Sam to their quest.
        Quotes
            'I have not seen these tokens before,' said Aragorn. 'What do they
            mean?'
            'S is for Sauron,' said Gimli. 'That is easy to read.'
            'Nay!' said Legolas. 'Sauron does not use the Elf-runes.'
            'Neither does he use his right name, nor permit it to be spelt or
            spoken,' said Aragorn. 'And he does not use white. The Orcs in the
            service of Barad-dur use the sign of the Red Eye.' He stood for a
            moment in thought. 'S is for Saruman, I guess,' he said at length.
            'There is evil afoot in Isengard, and the West is no longer safe.
            It is as Gandalf feared: by some means the traitor Saruman has had
            news of our journey. It is likely too that he knows of Gandalf's
            fall. Pursuers from Moria may have escaped the vigilance of Lorien,
            or they may have avoided that land and come to Isengard by other
            paths. Orcs travel fast. But Saruman has many ways of learning
            news.'

            'But why should he leave us behind, and without a word?' said
            Gimli. 'That was a strange deed!'
            'And a brave deed,' said Aragorn.  'Sam was right, I think. Frodo
            did not wish to lead any friend to death with him in Mordor. But he
            knew that he must go himself.  Something happened after he left us
            that overcame his fear and doubt.'
            'Maybe hunting Orcs came on him and he fled,' said Legolas.
            'He fled, certainly,' said Aragorn, 'but not, I think, from Orcs.'
            What he thought was the cause of Frodo's sudden resolve and flight
            Aragorn did not say. The last words of Boromir he long kept secret.

            'Let me think!' said Aragorn. 'And now may I make a right choice
            and change the evil fate of this unhappy day!' He stood silent for
            a moment. 'I will follow the Orcs,' he said at last. 'I would have
            guided Frodo to Mordor and gone with him to the end; but if I seek
            him now in the wilderness, I must abandon the captives to torment
            and death. My heart speaks clearly at last: the fate of the Bearer
            is in my hands no longer. The Company has played its part. Yet we
            that remain cannot forsake our companions while we have strength
            left. Come! We will go now. Leave all that can be spared behind! We
            will press on by day and dark!'
